1
00:00:03,031 --> 00:00:06,617
At the Hyatt Regency, the deadly change looked like a shortcut.

2
00:00:07,599 --> 00:00:12,647
The walkway design used one continuous hangar rod from roof to fourth floor to second floor.

3
00:00:13,609 --> 00:00:18,237
In shop drawings, it became two shorter rods, easier to build.

4
00:00:19,198 --> 00:00:20,561
But the load path changed.

5
00:00:21,222 --> 00:00:25,088
The fourth floor connection now carried both walkways, not one.

6
00:00:25,850 --> 00:00:27,772
The load essentially doubled.

7
00:00:27,888 --> 00:00:31,596
NBS later found the original design was already weak.

8
00:00:31,615 --> 00:00:34,923
The revision left roughly one-third of code-expected capacity.

9
00:00:35,845 --> 00:00:41,277
On July 17, 1981, two walkways collapsed during a crowded dance.

10
00:00:42,079 --> 00:00:47,432
Official records count 113 dead and 186 injured.

11
00:00:47,868 --> 00:00:49,354
This was not a shop detail.

12
00:00:49,395 --> 00:00:52,207
It was a structural redesign.

13
00:00:53,192 --> 00:00:55,261
Every handoff treated it like paperwork.

14
00:00:55,863 --> 00:00:58,957
Small causes, massive consequences.
